{
  "texts": [
    "We denote by A d the set of formal Lipschitz sums.Expressions such as n i=1 (f i, π i) for n ∈ N are identified with the formal Lipschitz sum i (f i, π i) where f i = 0 and π i = 0 for i > n.Next, we define an equivalence relation ∼ on A d and then a vector space structure on A d / ∼.",
    "The equivalence relation is given by i(f i, π i) ∼ i (g i, κ i) if i T (f i, π i) = i T (g i, κ i) for every T ∈ D d.The definition if valid due to (iii) and Corollary 3.3.",
    "Indeed, the sums appearing in the definition are even guaranteed to be converging absolutely.Given a countable set S, any family{(f s, π s)} s∈S such that s∈S ∥f s ∥ L d j=1 Lip(π d s) < ∞,and any two bijectionsρ 1, ρ 2: N → S, i (f ρ 1 (i), π ρ 1 (i)) ∼ i (f ρ 2 (i), π ρ 2 (i)).Thus, we define the common value to be [ s (f s, π s)].Using this notation, we may define addition onA d / ∼ via [ i (f i, π i)] + [ i (g i, κ i)] = [ i,j∈N (f i, π i) + (g j, κ j)],We also define scalar multiplicationλ[ i (f i, π i)] = [ i (λf i, π i)].It is immediately verified that under these operations, A d / ∼ is a vector space.Observe the inequality (cf.",
    "(2.2))∥f det Dπ∥ L ∞ (Q) ≤ ∥f ∥ L d j=1Lip(π j), which guarantees, that whenever i (f i, π i) is a formal Lipschitz sum, the sum i f i det Dπ i converges absolutely in L ∞ (Q).",
    "Definition 3.5."
  ]
